{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"652"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/652"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.69,0.21,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104083"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104083"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with right earache of one week duration, associated with a blocked sensation and scant discharge. On otoscopic examination, there is an inflamed and occluded right ear canal with green-gray discharge and pain upon moving his pinna. The left ear is normal. His Weber test lateralised to the right and the Rinne shows bone conduction greater than air conduction on the right and air conduction greater than bone conduction on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furuncle","Otitis externa","Otitis media with tympanic membrane perforation","Cholesteatoma","Pinna cellulitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man is presenting with right ear pain, discharge, an inflamed and occluded ear canal and conductive hearing loss on the right. This is classic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eotitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E. This ear discharge is an important feature of otitis externa and helps to also distinguish it from the \u003Cstrong\u003Epinna cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E. A \u003Cstrong\u003Efuruncle\u003C/strong\u003E is an infected hair follicle and these follicles are found in the lateral one-third of the ear canal. However, a furuncle is less likely to cause hearing loss. \u003Cstrong\u003EOtitis media with tympanic membrane perforation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echolesteatoma\u003C/strong\u003E will both be visible on otoscopy (otitis media with tympanic membrane perforation visualised as an inflamed tympanic membrane with perforation and cholesteatoma visualised as a retraction pocket seen in the attic or posterosuperior quadrant of a tympanic membrane) and is not associated with ear canal inflammation. Pinna cellulitis is unlikely to cause conductive hearing loss or ear canal inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ear discharge is a key symptom in otitis externa."],"references":["eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Vic): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd;  2019. Acute Diffuse Otitis Externa [updated 2019 Apr; cited 2021 Feb 15]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=otitis-externa\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e47","Kim S, Chang P. Cholesteatoma-diagnosing the unsafe ear. Australian family physician. 2008 Aug;37(8):631."]},